                 case "Sulfur":
                System.out.println("Sulfur or sulphur is a chemical element with symbol S and atomic number 16."+ "\n It is abundant, multivalent, and nonmetallic. Under normal conditions, sulfur atoms form cyclic octatomic molecules." +"\n Sulfur is the tenth most common element by mass in the universe, and the fifth most common on Earth."
                        + "\n Electron configuration: [Ne]3s^23p^4 " +"\n Physical Properties" + "\n Phase at STP: solid" +"\n Melting point: 388.36K" + "\n Boiling point: 717.8K" +"\n Density: (near r.t.) 2.07g/cm^3(alpha), 1.96g/cm^3(beta), 1.92g/cm^3(gamma), 1.819g/cm^3(M.P)");
                break; 
                 case "Chlorine":
                System.out.println("Chlorine is a chemical element with symbol Cl and atomic number 17."+ "\n The second-lightest of the halogens, it appears between fluorine and bromine in the periodic table and its properties are mostly intermediate between them." +"\n It is the second-most abundant halogen (after fluorine) and twenty-first most abundant chemical element in Earth's crust."
                        + "\n Electron configuration: [Ne]3s^23p^5 " +"\n Physical Properties" + "\n Phase at STP: gas" +"\n Melting point: 171.6K" + "\n Boiling point: 239.11K" +"\n Density: 3.2g/L(STP), 1.5625g/cm^3(B.P)");
